1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,355
Now that we've discussed how to build a histogram,

2

00:00:03,355  -->  00:00:07,550
we can use this to determine the shape associated with our data.

3

00:00:07,550  -->  00:00:09,875
Here we have three histograms,

4

00:00:09,875  -->  00:00:13,300
showing the shape for three different data sets.

5

00:00:13,300  -->  00:00:17,675
The histogram that has shorter bins on the left and taller bins on the right,

6

00:00:17,675  -->  00:00:20,419
is considered a left skewed shape.

7

00:00:20,419  -->  00:00:24,530
This histogram that has shorter bins on the right and taller bins on the left,

8

00:00:24,530  -->  00:00:26,860
is considered a right skewed shape.

9

00:00:26,860  -->  00:00:30,670
Any distribution where you can draw a line down the middle and

10

00:00:30,670  -->  00:00:35,290
the right side mirrors the left side is considered symmetric.

11

00:00:35,290  -->  00:00:38,100
One of the most common symmetric distributions,

12

00:00:38,100  -->  00:00:42,765
is known as a normal distribution and it's also called the Bell Curve.

13

00:00:42,765  -->  00:00:46,110
The shape of the distribution can actually tell us

14

00:00:46,110  -->  00:00:49,629
a lot about the measures of center and spread.

15

00:00:49,629  -->  00:00:54,829
Symmetric distributions, like this one have a mean that's equal to the median,

16

00:00:54,829  -->  00:00:57,360
which also equals the mode.

17

00:00:57,360  -->  00:01:00,720
Each of these measures sits here in the center.

18

00:01:00,720  -->  00:01:05,195
The mode is essentially the tallest bar in our histogram.

19

00:01:05,195  -->  00:01:07,730
When we have skewed distributions,

20

00:01:07,730  -->  00:01:11,140
it's the case of the mean is pulled by the tail of the distribution,

21

00:01:11,140  -->  00:01:13,580
while the median stays closer to the mode.

22

00:01:13,580  -->  00:01:16,685
For example, in this right skewed distribution,

23

00:01:16,685  -->  00:01:18,440
the mean would be pulled higher,

24

00:01:18,440  -->  00:01:21,575
resulting in a mean that's greater than our median.

25

00:01:21,575  -->  00:01:24,962
Alternatively, in a left skewed distribution,

26

00:01:24,962  -->  00:01:26,720
our mean is pulled down here,

27

00:01:26,720  -->  00:01:30,455
resulting in a mean that's less than our median.

28

00:01:30,455  -->  00:01:33,675
In order to relate this to the visual of a histogram,

29

00:01:33,675  -->  00:01:37,380
back to the five number summary we saw on the earlier lessons,

30

00:01:37,380  -->  00:01:42,060
here are the corresponding box plots below each histogram.

31

00:01:42,060  -->  00:01:45,240
Notice how the whiskers stretch in the direction of the skew,

32

00:01:45,240  -->  00:01:47,490
for each of the skewed distributions.

33

00:01:47,490  -->  00:01:50,355
That is the longer whisker is on the left,

34

00:01:50,355  -->  00:01:53,070
for a left skewed distribution and it's on the right,

35

00:01:53,070  -->  00:01:55,100
for the right skewed distribution.

36

00:01:55,100  -->  00:02:01,060
Alternatively, the symmetric histogram also has a symmetric box spot.
